8 Conversions Between Pure and Tcl Values
*****************************************

As far as pure-tk is concerned, all Tcl values are strings (in fact,
that's just what they are at the Tcl language level, although the Tcl
interpreter uses more elaborate representations of objects such as
lists internally).  There are no automatic conversions of any kind.
Thus, the arguments passed to a Pure callback and the result returned
by *note tk: d. are simply strings in Pure land. The same holds for the
*note tk_set: 13. and *note tk_get: 15. functions.

  However, there are a few helper functions which can be used to
convert between Tcl and Pure data. First, the following operations
convert Pure lists to corresponding Tcl lists and vice versa:

 -- Function: tk_join xs
 -- Function: tk_split s
     convert between Pure and Tcl lists

    > tk_join ["0","1.0","Hello, world!"];
    "0 1.0 {Hello, world!}"
    > tk_split ans;
    ["0","1.0","Hello, world!"]

The *note tk_str: 19. and *note tk_val: 1a. operations work in a
similar fashion, but they also do automatic conversions for numeric
values (ints, bigints and doubles):

 -- Function: tk_str xs
 -- Function: tk_val s
     convert between Pure and Tcl values with numeric conversions

    > tk_str [0,1.0,"Hello, world!"];
    "0 1.0 {Hello, world!}"
    > tk_val ans;
    [0,1.0,"Hello, world!"]

In addition, these operations also convert single atomic values:

    > tk_str 1.0;
    "1.0"
    > tk_val ans;
    1.0



